In 2015, UNICEF released a report detailing the extensive ramifications of women’s lack of bodily autonomy in El Salvador, describing the violence and social disenfranchisement that women endure in the culture that surrounds their lack of abortion rights. Women who seek abortion are often punished severely, and strip away the agency of women reluctant to undergo childbirth. Only a very limited number of women in El Salvador have actual legal rights to an abortion, forcing many women through grueling trial, and prison time.
Part of the reason for the constant presence of state sanction can be blamed on the
dictatorship of the country’s armed forces until 1989. During the dictatorship, the death of a pregnant woman was criminalized in El Salvador’s Criminal Code. Perforations of the uterus and poison were considered ways of aborting the fetus, and thus described as crimes against humanity. A woman’s fetus became an aspect of the nation’s body politic; any act that could cause damage (of any kind) to it was regarded as a crime deserving of punishment of criminalizing the pregnant woman.
More extreme examples of punishing pregnant women include the story of Beatriz Espinoza Salazar. She was a 22-year-old member of indigenous community of Cacaopera in the department of Cabañas; she carried triplets for her 37-weeks’ pregnancy when she fell into a coma
